SIMPLE: stagger
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stagger
<hw>Stag"ger</hw> <pr>(-g⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Staggered</conjf>
<pr>(-g⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Staggering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>stakeren</ets>,
Icel. <ets>stakra</ets> to push, to stagger, fr. <ets>staka</ets> to
punt, push, stagger; cf. OD. <ets>staggeren</ets> to stagger. Cf.
<er>Stake</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move to one
side and the other, as if about to fall, in standing or walking; not to
stand or walk with steadiness; to sway; to reel or totter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Deep was the wound; he <qex>staggered</qex> with the blow.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cease to stand firm; to begin to give way; to
fail.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The enemy <xex>staggers</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To begin to doubt and waver in purpose; to become
less confident or determined; to hesitate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He [Abraham] <qex>staggered</qex> not at the promise of God
through unbelief.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. iv. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stagger</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stagger
<hw>Stag"ger</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to reel or
totter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That hand shall burn in never-quenching fire⟦br⟧
That <qex>staggers</qex> thus my person.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to doubt and waver; to make to hesitate; to
make less steady or confident; to shock.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whosoever will read the story of this war will find himself much
<qex>staggered</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Howell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grants to the house of Russell were so enormous, as not only to
outrage economy, but even to <qex>stagger</qex> credibility.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To arrange (a series of parts) on each side of a
median line alternately, as the spokes of a wheel or the rivets of a
boiler seam.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stagger</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stagger
<hw>Stag"ger</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An unsteady movement
of the body in walking or standing, as if one were about to fall; a
reeling motion; vertigo; -- often in the plural; <as>as, the
<ex>stagger</ex> of a drunken man</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>A disease of
horses and other animals, attended by reeling, unsteady gait or sudden
falling; <as>as, parasitic <ex>staggers</ex>; apoplectic or sleepy
<ex>staggers</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Bewilderment; perplexity.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stomach staggers</b></col> <fld>(Far.)</fld>,
<cd>distention of the stomach with food or gas, resulting in
indigestion, frequently in death.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Staggerbush</ent>⟦br⟧
